those perfect fifths

00:38:32.560 --> 00:38:35.650
in ascending order, from
lowest note to highest note.

00:38:35.650 --> 00:38:59.590
[MUSICAL NOTES]

00:38:59.590 --> 00:39:00.792
That's a pentatonic scale.

00:39:00.792 --> 00:39:03.000
Now one thing that's
interesting is that that scale's

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:05.000
been used in most cultures.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:06.670
It's one scale.

00:39:06.670 --> 00:39:09.280
But let me do some more things
are that pentatonic scale.

00:39:09.280 --> 00:39:25.100
[MUSICAL NOTES]

00:39:25.100 --> 00:39:26.970
That's a blues scale.

00:39:26.970 --> 00:39:30.160
So the point here is that one
of the most used scales in all

00:39:30.160 --> 00:39:33.130
of our-- is just
a sophistication,

00:39:33.130 --> 00:39:36.770
a tiny sophistication over a
scale that's just generated

00:39:36.770 --> 00:39:39.870
naturally from the
laws of physics,

00:39:39.870 --> 00:39:41.830
just from the perfect
fifth relation.

00:39:41.830 --> 00:39:44.970
And so it's no mistake
why "A Love Supreme," one

00:39:44.970 --> 00:39:47.590
of Coltrane's greatest
works, is rooted

00:39:47.590 --> 00:39:49.030
in this pentatonic scale.

00:39:49.030 --> 00:39:52.100
So when Coltrane told David
Amram, the great composer,

00:39:52.100 --> 00:39:55.990
that like Einstein, I am seeking
for something simple that

00:39:55.990 --> 00:39:58.960
brings music together
from natural sources,

00:39:58.960 --> 00:40:02.600
it couldn't be nothing
but this pentatonic scale.

00:40:02.600 --> 00:40:03.360
All right.

