analogy-making game,

00:43:37.290 --> 00:43:39.525
you can always find these
overlapping domains.

00:43:39.525 --> 00:43:41.400
And then there's something
interesting there.

00:43:41.400 --> 00:43:44.010
Because then where
they overlap and where

00:43:44.010 --> 00:43:46.920
the analogies break down is
where something interesting

00:43:46.920 --> 00:43:48.446
might flourish.

00:43:48.446 --> 00:43:49.820
And in the book,
I talk about-- I

00:43:49.820 --> 00:43:54.580
go into-- it's really also
a book, for me, about doing

00:43:54.580 --> 00:43:55.130
research.

00:43:55.130 --> 00:43:57.800
I mean, when I work with
my graduate students,

00:43:57.800 --> 00:44:00.970
the question is, how do I enable
them to be better researchers?

00:44:00.970 --> 00:44:02.870
Not to just learn
physics, but how

00:44:02.870 --> 00:44:04.550
to do it, how to
write new papers,

00:44:04.550 --> 00:44:06.180
how to come up with new ideas.

00:44:06.180 --> 00:44:10.170
And this way of-- I realize
that all of my years

00:44:10.170 --> 00:44:14.670
trying to be a jazz improviser
and playing spontaneously

00:44:14.670 --> 00:44:16.570
on the spot with other
people and having them

00:44:16.570 --> 00:44:19.880
support me, and function
with that group of people,

00:44:19.880 --> 00:44:21.870
not being selfish--
all these things

00:44:21.870 --> 00:44:24.190
are elements in
the research front

00:44:24.190 --> 00:44:26.451
that I found to be
very useful with how

00:44:26.451 --> 00:44:28.950
I interact with my colleagues,
how I interact with students.

00:44:31.800 --> 00:44:34.160
I do think there's
something special.

00:44:34.160 --> 00:44:38.882
But I also think that if
you do this analogy-making

00:44:38.882 --> 00:44:41.340
with other fields, there'll be
something special and unique

00:44:41.340 --> 00:44:42.810
there as well, too.

00:44:42.810 --> 00:44:44.740
AUDIENCE: Could you
explain that Coltrane

00:44:44.740 --> 00:44:46.630
diagram since you didn't
have time to get--

00:44:46.630 --> 00:44:48.320
STEPHON ALEXANDER: OK, sure.

00:44:48.320 --> 00:44:48.910
All right.

00:44:48.910 --> 00:44:54.340
So there's the
Coltrane diagram again.

00:44:54.340 --> 00:44:57.300
And going back to your thing--
so the diagram, I think,

00:44:57.300 --> 00:45:00.672
was-- one interesting thing is
that a lot of jazz, not all,

00:45:00.672 --> 00:45:02.380
are sort of trying to
do a similar thing.

00:45:02.380 --> 00:45:05.380
They want to come up with
their own sort of system,

00:45:05.380 --> 00:45:08.380
some kind of geometrical,
mathematical system,

00:45:08.380 --> 00:45:12.320
because that enables them
to think more economically

00:45:12.320 --> 00:45:14.330
about how to improvise.

00:45:14.330 --> 00:45:16.890
Because, you know
there's many of thousands

00:45:16.890 --> 00:45:18.155
of different scales.

00:45:18.155 --> 00:45:18.780
You're playing.

00:45:18.780 --> 00:45:19.770
What do you do?

00:45:19.770 --> 00:45:26.180
So a lot of improvisers come
up with tricks of the trade.

00:45:26.180 --> 00:45:31.390
So this diagram I claim
was some sort of thing

00:45:31.390 --> 00:45:35.180
that Coltrane was trying
to systematize relationship

00:45:35.180 --> 00:45:38.580
between scales and
harmonic relations

00:45:38.580 --> 00:45:40.480
that was important to him.

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:44.800
So what you see here,
again, is a 60-sided cycle.

00:45:44.800 --> 00:45:48.200
Now in terms of math,
there's something

00:45:48.200 --> 00:45:50.290
called cyclical groups.

00:45:50.290 --> 00:45:54.780
So the group Z12 is a
group, a [? mod ?] 12,

00:45:54.780 --> 00:45:59.930
where you go around 12 times
and you come back to yourself.

00:45:59.930 --> 00:46:03.430
So Z60 is our 60-fold cycle.

00:46:03.430 --> 00:46:06.793
So if you really look closely,
you have 60 notes there.

00:46:06.793 --> 00:46:08.334
And then what happens
there, you see,

00:46:08.334 --> 00:46:11.670
you have clusters of those 60
notes, three clusters of notes.

00:46:11.670 --> 00:46:15.330
If you actually start with
the C and you go around--

00:46:15.330 --> 00:46:17.110
I can't point
out-- that actually

00:46:17.110 --> 00:46:19.870
is a very important
scale that I think

00:46:19.870 --> 00:46:25.200
[INAUDIBLE] or Schoenberg,
one of those people

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:29.610
who did group theory, applied
group theory to music.

00:46:29.610 --> 00:46:33.530
That's now called all
intervalic tetrachord.

00:46:33.530 --> 00:46:35.050
And there are two of them.

00:46:35.050 --> 00:46:39.919
And that system exists
in this diagram.

00:46:39.919 --> 00:46:42.210
The other thing that I'd also
say that's very important

00:46:42.210 --> 00:46:46.370
here is that you have
the whole tone scale.

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:51.200
"Giant Steps" is basically
based on the augmented triad.

00:46:54.130 --> 00:46:57.400
But you can actually make two
whole tone scales out of that.

00:46:57.400 --> 00:47:00.400
And these are what we
call symmetric scales.

00:47:00.400 --> 00:47:04.300
These are scales that
literally look symmetric

00:47:04.300 --> 00:47:06.670
when you geometrize
them in terms

00:47:06.670 --> 00:47:09.530
of these cycles, these
cyclical symmetries.

00:47:09.530 --> 00:47:11.140
The other thing
that's important here

00:47:11.140 --> 00:47:14.550
is something called a tritone,
which is a reflection.

00:47:14.550 --> 00:47:17.990
If I reflect along C and
I come back down here,

00:47:17.990 --> 00:47:19.020
I get the tritone.

00:47:19.020 --> 00:47:24.870
And that maintains
itself in this diagram.

00:47:24.870 --> 00:47:27.700
So it's not like a higher
dimensional version

00:47:27.700 --> 00:47:31.770
of our 12-tone scale
that contains scalar

00:47:31.770 --> 00:47:34.970
relationships in the geometry.

00:47:34.970 --> 00:47:37.600
And you can now
ask yourself, you

00:47:37.600 --> 00:47:39.770
can think about now
relativity theory.

00:47:39.770 --> 00:47:42.266
And relativity
theory, as you know,

00:47:42.266 --> 00:47:48.730
if I-- what special
relatively tells me

00:47:48.730 --> 00:47:51.140
is that if I have
two observers moving

00:47:51.140 --> 00:47:53.150
at some velocity with
respect to each other,

00:47:53.150 --> 00:47:57.030
length will be contracted
for the fast-moving observer

00:47:57.030 --> 00:48:01.210
relative to the observer
that's not moving.

00:48:01.210 --> 00:48:03.380
And also time will
be dilated, meaning

00:48:03.380 --> 00:48:06.130
so the rate at which a clock
will tick for that moving

00:48:06.130 --> 00:48:09.260
observer will slow down
relative to the observer that's

00:48:09.260 --> 00:48:12.950
not moving, relative to
that observer's clock.

00:48:12.950 --> 00:48:14.560
So those things are
relative concepts.

00:48:14.560 --> 00:48:17.020
Space and time intervals
are relative concepts

00:48:17.020 --> 00:48:19.260
at the expense of
the speed of light

00:48:19.260 --> 00:48:21.860
actually being the same in
both frames of reference.

00:48:21.860 --> 00:48:24.940
So there's something
invariant about that geometry,

00:48:24.940 --> 00:48:29.394
of those spatial,
temporal relationships.

00:48:29.394 --> 00:48:30.810
There's something
invariant there,

00:48:30.810 --> 00:48:33.470
which is the speed
of light, which

00:48:33.470 --> 00:48:38.100
basically retains the length of
the four-dimensional geometry.

00:48:38.100 --> 00:48:40.700
So the thing that's
actually invariant

00:48:40.700 --> 00:48:42.600
is a four-dimensional
lengths measured

00:48:42.600 --> 00:48:45.750
in the four-dimensional length.

00:48:45.750 --> 00:48:48.840
So Coltrane tired to-- I
believe he read everything

00:48:48.840 --> 00:48:50.590
he could get his hands
on about Einstein--

00:48:50.590 --> 00:48:55.450
he was trying to find, OK, you
know these different scalar

00:48:55.450 --> 00:48:57.690
relationships are kind
of relative to each other

00:48:57.690 --> 00:48:59.270
in this geometry.

00:48:59.270 --> 00:49:04.620
But the thing that's invariant
is the 60-fold cycle.

00:49:04.620 --> 00:49:05.920
And that's the basic idea.

00:49:05.920 --> 00:49:11.450
Now, of course, I in
the book go into-- I

00:49:11.450 --> 00:49:14.490
try to develop the language so
that even if you know nothing

00:49:14.490 --> 00:49:17.470
about music theory, by the time
you get to the end of the book,

00:49:17.470 --> 00:49:20.030
you're like, OK, I
can use this language.

00:49:20.030 --> 00:49:22.780
The other thing that's really
cool in this diagram-- and this

00:49:22.780 --> 00:49:27.310
is a conjecture-- so "The New
York Times" review, basically,

00:49:27.310 --> 00:49:28.210
tried to get at me.

00:49:28.210 --> 00:49:29.600
I basically tried
to riff on this

00:49:29.600 --> 00:49:34.950
because a lot of what goes
on, too, in theory-making

00:49:34.950 --> 00:49:38.100
and also jazz music
is that we riff.

00:49:38.100 --> 00:49:40.880
We make mistakes.

00:49:40.880 --> 00:49:43.710
If I tell someone get up
here, get on my sax, and just

00:49:43.710 --> 00:49:46.280
improvise, and if
you go in thinking

00:49:46.280 --> 00:49:49.170
that you want to play something
perfect, you'll freeze up.

00:49:49.170 --> 00:49:51.940
But if you go in, and
knowing that improvisation

00:49:51.940 --> 00:49:54.570
is about making
mistakes, and learning

00:49:54.570 --> 00:50:02.450
how to fall in real time,
then you could improvise.

00:50:02.450 --> 00:50:06.050
So it's about when you play
that wrong note-- you will--

00:50:06.050 --> 00:50:07.980
how like an acrobat you fall.

00:50:07.980 --> 00:50:10.750
And that becomes
interesting improvisation.

00:50:10.750 --> 00:50:11.906
So I riff on this.

00:50:11.906 --> 00:50:13.280
And I said this
had this-- if you

00:50:13.280 --> 00:50:17.700
look at this four-pointed
triangle, pentagram,

00:50:17.700 --> 00:50:20.340
I started to say,
well, maybe this

00:50:20.340 --> 00:50:26.551
led to this pentatonic scale,
this five-fold symmetry.

00:50:26.551 --> 00:50:28.676
Now here's a puzzle that
I haven't figured out yet.

00:50:28.676 --> 00:50:30.380
So maybe you guys can
help me with this.

00:50:30.380 --> 00:50:33.030
The pentagram does have a--
in terms of group theory,

00:50:33.030 --> 00:50:34.280
it has a five-fold symmetry.

00:50:38.270 --> 00:50:41.090
If I perform discrete
transformations

00:50:41.090 --> 00:50:43.620
on the edges of
this pentagram, it

00:50:43.620 --> 00:50:46.940
remains invariant in
a five-fold manner.

00:50:46.940 --> 00:50:48.150
That's pretty cool.

00:50:48.150 --> 00:50:49.990
But if I start
coloring this diagram

00:50:49.990 --> 00:50:53.090
with notes of the
pentatonic scale,

00:50:53.090 --> 00:50:56.090
it's no longer invariant.

00:50:56.090 --> 00:50:56.820
All right.

00:50:56.820 --> 00:51:01.090
So the puzzle is, how
do I make it invariant?

00:51:01.090 --> 00:51:04.320
I suspect that the
answer to that puzzle

00:51:04.320 --> 00:51:08.850
reveals I think what Coltrane
didn't reveal to anybody else.

00:51:08.850 --> 00:51:11.510
I think he left us as a
puzzle to Yusef Lateef.

00:51:11.510 --> 00:51:14.610
Yusef Lateef was known to
be the guy of knowledge

00:51:14.610 --> 00:51:15.930
to all the jazz musicians.

00:51:15.930 --> 00:51:20.020
They used to get out to Detroit.

00:51:20.020 --> 00:51:21.660
Coltrane and, I
think, Charles Mingus

00:51:21.660 --> 00:51:25.150
and asked him theory questions.

00:51:25.150 --> 00:51:27.540
So I think they had this
kind of relationship,

00:51:27.540 --> 00:51:30.170
just like Einstein
and Godel had.

00:51:30.170 --> 00:51:30.920
Thank you.

00:51:30.920 --> 00:51:32.961
MALE SPEAKER: Let's thank
Stephon Alexander for--

00:51:32.990 --> 00:51:33.290
[APPLAUSE]

00:51:33.290 --> 00:51:34.498
STEPHON ALEXANDER: Thank you.

00:51:34.498 --> 00:51:36.940
Thanks for having me.

